A transaction log is a form of maintaining a history of changes happening to the data store. 
It can be reapplied on each restart, crash, etc.

It can be also used to put the program back in the desired state. It can also be
replayed back to rewind changes -- just a few ideas.

It is read-only on restart and is read sequentially, in a linear fashion, top to bottom.

The log is append only.

Each record has the following attributes:
1. sequence number (ID, for short) -- an integer i from a sequence of 1, 2, 3, ..., n
2. event type -- CRUD action, PUT and DELETE (GET is not needed)
3. key -- the affected key string
4. value -- the string value stored under a given key

There two major issues with this kind of logging:
1. One has to find a way to distribute the logged state between nodes when scaling up/down.
2. Log files are stored on disk, and they cannot grow forever, one has to figure out how to
make them more compact.
